<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1842" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1842">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.673/40.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Turkish Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Ottoman Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 17, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge receipt
                            of your note of yesterday’s date replying to my note of the 10th inst
                            informing the Government of the United States of the decision of the
                            Sublime Porte to abrogate the Capitulations as from the 1st of October
                            next.</p>
                        <p>I notice that at the same time as the Government of the United States
                            does not recognize the right of the Ottoman Government to set aside the
                            Capitulations it does not acquiesce in the latter’s endeavour to free
                            itself from them. This I take to mean that the principle itself of the
                            removal of these restrictions on Turkish sovereignty is to be opposed by
                            the United States.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.].</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">A. Rustem</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>